  "created": "2025-10-14",
  "description": "The Yeast ER-Associated Degradation (ERAD) pathway is a crucial quality control mechanism in *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* that identifies and eliminates misfolded proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum (ER). This process begins with the detection of misfolded proteins, either in the ER lumen (ERAD-L) or embedded in the ER membrane (ERAD-M), often triggered by ER stress. Luminal substrates are recognized by chaperones like BiP, Sec63, Lhs1, and PDI, which then recruit the Hrd3 ERAD receptor. Membrane substrates interact directly with the Hrd1 E3 ubiquitin ligase or involve the Der1 receptor and Usa1. These recognition events converge on the formation of the Hrd1 retrotranslocon complex, which includes the Sec61 channel, critical for dislocating proteins back to the cytosol. The Hrd1 E3 ligase, in conjunction with E1 and E2 (Ubc7/Ubc1) enzymes, catalyzes the polyubiquitination of the misfolded protein. The specificity of E2 enzymes, as highlighted by Swarnkar et al. (2024), determines ubiquitin chain linkage. The polyubiquitinated substrate is then extracted from the ER by the cytosolic AAA-ATPase complex, Cdc48/Ufd1/Npl4, which utilizes ATP hydrolysis for mechanical pulling. Once in the cytosol, the protein undergoes deglycosylation by Png1 and may be deubiquitinated by DUBs before being targeted to the 26S proteasome for degradation into peptides and amino acids, ensuring ER homeostasis.",
  "id": "yeast_yeast_er_associated_degradation",
